    })}
  </AnimatePresence>
</main>
```

Next, define the animations for your `CarteProgrammation` component. You can define an "initial", "animate", and "exit" state for your card component. This will allow the cards to animate in upon entering, animate while present, and animate out upon leaving.

```javascript
// Define your animation variants somewhere in your component:
const cardVariants = {
  initial: { opacity: 0, y: 50 },
  animate: { opacity: 1, y: 0 },
  exit: { opacity: 0, y: -50 },
};

// Then, use these variants in your individual card component:
<motion.div
  className="outer-carte-artiste"
  ref={refCarte}
  variants={cardVariants}
  initial="initial"
  animate="animate"
  exit="exit"
  // ... rest of your props ...
>
  {/* Your existing card markup */}
</motion.div>
```

These variants will cause the cards to fade and move into place smoothly when they appear in the list and do the reverse when they disappear due to the search filter.

Make sure you have keys set on the `motion.div` that wraps `CarteProgrammation` to allow `AnimatePresence` to track which elements are entering and exiting correctly:

```javascript
<AnimatePresence>
  {filteredGroupes.map((groupe) => (
    <motion.div key={groupe.idG} ...animated attributes... >
      <CarteProgrammation ...props... />
    </motion.div>
  ))}
  {filteredArtistes.map((artiste) => (
    <motion.div key={artiste.idMG} ...animated attributes... >
      <CarteProgrammation ...props... />
    </motion.div>
  ))}
</AnimatePresence>
```

Using `AnimatePresence`, you can also control the animation sequencing, such as adding `staggerChildren` to `motion.div` or using delay properties in your animations, to have the cards come in one after the other for a more dynamic effect. Adjust the values in the `cardVariants` to achieve the animation timing and style you desire.

